Yes, it is possible to solve this problem without using loops or recursion. Here is one solution using bitwise operations:
```
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // Check if n is negative
        if (n < 0) return false;

        // Check if n is a power of three
        int count = 0;
        while (n != 0) {
            int r = n % 3;
            if (r != 0) {
                count++;
            }
            n /= 3;
        }

        // Return true if count is 1
        return count == 1;
    }
}
```
This solution first checks if n is negative. If it is, then it immediately returns false.

Next, it uses a while loop to check if n is a power of three. Inside the while loop, it uses the modulo operator (%) to check if the remainder of n when divided by 3 is 0. If it is, then n is a power of three and count is incremented.

Finally, it returns true if count is 1, which means that n is either 3^1 = 3 or 3^2 = 9, which are the only two powers of three less than or equal to 231.

