public class Solution {
    public ListNode deleteDuplicates(ListNode head) {
        ListNode hashMap = new ListNode(0);
        ListNode current = head;
        while (current != null) {
            if (!hashMap.nextExcept(current)) {
                hashMap.next = current;
            }
            current = current.next;
        }
        return hashMap.next;
    }
}
```
This solution uses a hash table (implemented as a ListNode) to store the unique numbers in the linked list. As we traverse the linked list, we check if the current node's value is already in the hash table. If it is not, we add it to the hash table and move on to the next node. If it is, we move on to the next node without adding it to the hash table. This way, we only store unique values in the hash table.

At the end, we return the next node of the hash table, which will be a linked list containing only the unique values.
